Mini report¶

In this project I analysis the land values of differents areas in France using the datasets from 'https://www.data.gouv.fr/fr/datasets/demandes-de-valeurs-foncieres/'.

I started this project by selecting most useful assets from the dataset. I then observesd the obtained pandas DataFrame and processed the data to allow a deep data analysis later given that I already had my visualization ideas in mind.

However, I still encountered a problem: some data was outlier, such as the exorbitant price per square meter in Brittany compared to the rest of France. To address this issue, I performed a more thorough data cleaning.

I decided to focus on comparisons between regions and departments. For the comparison between four years, I choose 2024 and 2020, the latter being an interesting year due to the Covid-19 pandemic.

Finally, I created two visualizations on Django: the property value by type of property and by month, as well as a map of France showing the property value by region.

def format_code_postal(cp):
    if pd.isna(cp):
        return None 
    cp = int(float(cp))
    cp_str = str(cp)
    if len(cp_str) < 5:
        cp_str = cp_str.ljust(5, '0')
    return cp_str

df2024['Code postal'] = df2024['Code postal'].apply(format_code_postal)
df2020['Code postal'] = df2020['Code postal'].apply(format_code_postal)

We observe that the regions with the highest number of properties in 2020 have experienced a decrease in property numbers in 2024, while the regions that had fewer properties in 2020 are showing growth in their number of properties compared to 2024. Surely due to the Covid-19 Pandemic.

# Load the GeoJSON file for French regions
with open('regions.geojson', 'r') as file:
    regions_geo = json.load(file)

# Calculate the average property value per region for 2020
average_price_per_region = df2020.groupby('Region')['Valeur fonciere'].mean().reset_index()
# Définir les bornes de l'échelle selon les quantiles des valeurs foncières
bins = list(average_price_per_region['Valeur fonciere'].quantile([0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1]))

# Create a folium map centered on France
france_map = folium.Map(location=[46.603354, 1.888334], zoom_start=5)

folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=regions_geo,
    name='choropleth',
    data=average_price_per_region,
    columns=['Region', 'Valeur fonciere'],
    key_on='feature.properties.nom',
    fill_color='YlOrRd',
    fill_opacity=0.7,
    line_opacity=0.2,
    legend_name='Average property value by region (2020)',
    bins=bins
).add_to(france_map)

folium.LayerControl().add_to(france_map)

import calendar

df2020['Year'] = '2020'
df2024['Year'] = '2024'

data_combined = pd.concat([df2020, df2024])
monthly_mean_prices = data_combined.groupby([data_combined['Date mutation'].dt.month, 'Year'])['Valeur fonciere'].mean().unstack()

monthly_mean_prices = monthly_mean_prices.reindex(list(range(1, 13)))

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(monthly_mean_prices.index, monthly_mean_prices['2020'], label='2020')
plt.plot(monthly_mean_prices.index, monthly_mean_prices['2024'], label='2024')
plt.title('Evolution of average price over time')
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Average price')
plt.legend()
plt.xticks(monthly_mean_prices.index, calendar.month_name[1:], rotation=45)
plt.show()
